hands_on_practices.problem:
Consider a balanced three-phase, three-wire sinusoidal system supplying a load with unity power factor. Let the phase-to-neutral voltages be given by
$$
v_{a}(t)=V_{m}\cos(\omega t),\quad v_{b}(t)=V_{m}\cos\!\left(\omega t-\frac{2\pi}{3}\right),\quad v_{c}(t)=V_{m}\cos\!\left(\omega t+\frac{2\pi}{3}\right),
$$
and the phase currents (due to unity power factor) be
$$
i_{a}(t)=I_{m}\cos(\omega t),\quad i_{b}(t)=I_{m}\cos\!\left(\omega t-\frac{2\pi}{3}\right),\quad i_{c}(t)=I_{m}\cos\!\left(\omega t+\frac{2\pi}{3}\right),
$$
where $V_{m}$ and $I_{m}$ are the peak (maximum) values of the phase voltage and current, respectively, and all angles are in radians. Define the Clarke transformation (also known as the $\alpha\beta$ transformation) from $abc$ to $\alpha\beta$ coordinates by
$$
\begin{pmatrix}
v_{\alpha} \\
v_{\beta}
\end{pmatrix}
=\frac{2}{3}
\begin{pmatrix}
1 & -\frac{1}{2} & -\frac{1}{2} \\
0 & \frac{\sqrt{3}}{2} & -\frac{\sqrt{3}}{2}
\end{pmatrix}
\begin{pmatrix}
v_{a} \\
v_{b} \\
v_{c}
\end{pmatrix},\qquad
\begin{pmatrix}
i_{\alpha} \\
i_{\beta}
\end{pmatrix}
=\frac{2}{3}
\begin{pmatrix}
1 & -\frac{1}{2} & -\frac{1}{2} \\
0 & \frac{\sqrt{3}}{2} & -\frac{\sqrt{3}}{2}
\end{pmatrix}
\begin{pmatrix}
i_{a} \\
i_{b} \\
i_{c}
\end{pmatrix}.
$$
Starting from the definition of instantaneous three-phase power $p_{abc}(t)=v_{a}(t)i_{a}(t)+v_{b}(t)i_{b}(t)+v_{c}(t)i_{c}(t)$ and the above Clarke transformation, use the space vector representation to:
1) show that the instantaneous reactive power $q(t)$ is identically zero and the instantaneous real power $p(t)$ is constant in time under the stated conditions, and
2) compute the constant value of $p$ in closed form in terms of $V_{m}$ and $I_{m}$.

Express your final answer symbolically in terms of $V_{m}$ and $I_{m}$ only. Express power in watts. Do not include units inside the final reported expression.
